entry.title: sensors: Read Euler angles instead of quaternions from WebDriver
entry.content:
As a result of https://github.com/w3c/deviceorientation/pull/124 and

https://github.com/w3c/orientation-sensor/pull/83.



The reading format is alpha-beta-gamma as described in the spec. They

are measured in degrees and must fall within certain ranges. Internally,

however, we always perform the Euler angles to quaternions conversion at

the edges (i.e. in ChromeDriver and the Internals implementation used by

content_shell), so that the the CDP and //services layers remain

unchanged and continue to support only quaternions and the

{ABSOLUTE,RELATIVE}_ORIENTATION_QUATERNION types for simplicity.



The code to convert Euler angles to quaternions was copied from

SensorInspectorAgent in Blink and is available for use by any callers

that need to validate Euler angles and convert them. The original code

remains in place because the entirety of the SensorInspectorAgent will

be removed soon due to the work on bug 1506995.



The test values for the orientation-sensor web tests had to be adapted:

we now provide the inputs as Euler angles. The expected values have

changed slightly as we had to find Euler _and_ quaternion values that

were easy enough to read.



Written in collaboration with Juha Vainio



Bug: 1506995, 1520912, 1520919

entry.title: Use Available-Dictionary request header when V2 backend is enabled
entry.content:
The latest spec discussed in IETF HTTPWG is using `Available-Dictionary`

request header name instead of `Sec-Available-Dictionary`.

Also in the value is using a Structured Field sf-binary sha256 hash

of the dictionary after [1].



So after this CL, when V2 backend is enabled, Chrome will set

`Available-Dictionary` header with a Structured Field sf-binary sha256 hash of the dictionary.



[1]: https://github.com/httpwg/http-extensions/pull/2680

entry.title: [Extensions] Test that confirms non-redundant starts of kStarting SW.
entry.content:
Before this change we didn't have a test that confirms that

ServiceWorkerTaskQueue::AddPendingTask()'s `needs_start_worker` var

prevents redundantly attempting to start a worker when it is kStarting.

We assume we are the only ones who can start a worker and use pending

events/tasks as a proxy for whether the worker is started.



If there are pending tasks to be run the worker is not attempted to be

started. If there are none it will attempt to start the worker. Pending

events/tasks are run/cleared in

ServiceWorkerTaskQueue::DidStartWorkerForScope(),

ServiceWorkerTaskQueue::DidStartWorkerFail(), and

ServiceWorkerTaskQueue::DidStartServiceWorkerContext().



However, this above logic does not prevent a started/running worker from

being redundantly started. The

extensions_features::kExtensionsServiceWorkerOptimizedEventDispatch

feature helps with that and is addressed in https://crrev.com/c/5166766.

entry.title: WebNN: Allocate extra bytes for XNNPACK input buffers
entry.content:
XNNPACK may read `XNN_EXTRA_BYTES` number of bytes beyond array bounds.

It may cause an out-of-bounds access issue if the caller fails to

allocate at least this many extra bytes after the tensor data passed to

XNNPACK [1].



This CL fixes this issue by allocating `XNN_EXTRA_BYTES` extra bytes for

input buffers, copying the input tensor data into these newly allocated

buffers and using them for XNNPACK Runtime setup.

entry.title: Revert "Don't run module shims before kernel32 gets loaded"
entry.content:
This reverts commit 430d8ebfe6d4033d47bbebec5ecc117e97b21688.



Reason for revert: crbug.com/1520945 regressions with network sandbox

We will try again to re-write the shims to not use the heap



Original change's description:

> Don't run module shims before kernel32 gets loaded

>

> There are several bugs with the sandbox shims, root caused as chromium

> sometimes accessing the Windows heap before it is safe to do so, when

> OS code attempts to call NtCreateSection or NtMapViewOfSection during

> super-early process start-up.

>

> NtCreateSection - used to bypass CIG checks for binaries not signed by

> Microsoft by brokering the syscall.

>

> NtMapViewOfSection - used to listen to DLL loads in case we want to

> also shim those DLLs.

>

> This change adds early exits to the shims when these APIs are called

> before kernel32 is loaded, to avoid needing to use the heap while the

> process is in this super-early startup phase. There is not a great

> publicly documented API we can use earlier, as Windows public API is

> generally in kernel32, ntdll is mostly undocumented.

>

> It should be safe to wait this long. For NtCreateSection because all

> the Chromium binaries depend on kernel32.dll For NtMapViewOfSection

> because kernel32.dll should get loaded before any other DLLs we try to

> shim at runtime.

>

> Verified manually with a smoke test that we can run chromium under

> page heap and under the conditions from crbug.com/1519187

entry.content:
This CL fixes a UAF in AXPlatformNodeWin::Navigate, when the

current node is an AXFragmentRoot and the direction is

NavigateDirection_Parent. In that case, the GetParent call ends up

in RenderWidgetHostViewAura::GetParentNativeViewAccessible, and

the ViewAccessibility object with it (which owns the IAccessible that

gets cleared here).



The general fix to this is to clear the parent accessible object

entry.title: Reland "Remove the GN indirection for non-shared-library Rust targets"
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit 2060d8532c91caad91b64bf694061e41073ebb2d



Remove a new use of `is_data_dep` which is no longer consumed

by the rust_target GN template.



Original change's description:

> Remove the GN indirection for non-shared-library Rust targets

>

> Previously Rust targets always went through a GN group which would

> redirect to the actual rlib/exe/proc-macro target. This was done for

> proc-macros where we want to direct from the current toolchain to the

> rust-host-build-tools toolchain, and not make all proc-macro

> dependencies be specified with the toolchain.

>

> It was also needed for shared libraries, since we want to insert

> dependencies into C++ code that depends on the Rust, and link them

> into the C++ itself not the Rust. We do this for the Cxx thunks

> that are generated and call to the secret-named Rust internals of

> the cxx bridge. For a shared library, if they are a dependency of

> the Rust target, they get linked in there instead of in C++. So we

> need a group that provides the dependency to C++ in that case. It

> would be really nice to find a way to avoid the group in this case

> though.

>

> Then, for consistency it was done for other types of targets (rlibs,

> exes) too.

>

> There's a good chance it was helpful for mixed GN/C++ targets which

> we have since deleted, as well, though I don't recall now.

>

> The problem with this is that dependencies on X are not really on X,

> they are on X__rlib, and not everything can be forwarded through

> automatically. One example is data_deps which we had to add an

> `is_data_dep` on the target dependency in order to forward through

> from the group. This is no longer needed. Another is aliased

> dependencies needed to specify the real target with the __rlib

> suffix, making this a very leaky abstraction.

>

> This became a problem when depending on a Rust binary in this CL:

> https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/5198906/15/chrome/test/BUILD.gn#8351

> Where depending on a C++ binary was fine, but the Rust binary

> would not be present on the bot.

>

> Now it's only used for proc-macros and shared libraries, and not for

> for rlibs and exes. This limits the complexity to these more narrow

> use cases and will significantly reduce its ability to get in the

> way of developers.

>

> In the process of collapsing the group into the main build target,

> I attempted to explain the dependency on the stdlib target in

> comments and noticed that we are unconditionally depending on

> stdlib_for_rust and stdlib_for_clang. Since we are depending on both,

> we can combine them and simplify things.

>

entry.title: [A11y] Adjust fix for "De-flake AccessibilityContenteditableDocsLi"
entry.content:
crrev.com/c/5180532 fixed a flake that was caused by previousOnLineId

being unexpectedly null. The fix was to find the highest LayoutInline

ancestor of a newly-attached text node and mark that inline object

dirty so that previousOnlineId values would be recalculated.



This fix introduced a performance regression in two tests where many

text nodes were during the test. Given that the flake being fixed seems

to be limited to a whitepsace-only node, attempt to improve performance

while preserving the fix by only marking the subtree dirty when a

whitespace-only node is attached.

entry.content:
Previously in crrev.com/c/5069843 we only expose the content/public

BFCache flag. That won't actually enable the BFCache flag on WebView

because we need to override WebContentsDelegate's

IsBackForwardCacheSupported(), which this CL does. Additionally, we

add a new WebView specific flag to control whether BFCache is

enabled on WebView specifically, since the content/public flag is

enabled by default.
